text:
Sorry, a bit late to the conversation... Re: fundamental vs price only: 

My take on it is that form and fundamentals are good for building scalable, higher risk, higher margin strategies where you would typically take large positions and have to be prepared for potentially large drawdowns. It’s also hard to build fundamentals for a massive population of participants because of the data sourcing and work required - this sort of feeds into the higher risk because you have to put more money on single selections to generate those scalable returns. 

Whereas looking at price action is good for building high turnover, low margin, high consistency strategies where you’re more predicting price direction rather than event outcomes. This also means you don’t necessarily need a big bank because of the potentially high consistency. Although this is less scalable in terms of margin compared to fundamentals, you can instead scale by creating “generic” concepts which can be easily transferable to similar markets without relying on having to source fundamental data, and you can spread the risk across many more selections. 

That’s all a big generalisation of course, but that’s the high level impression I get. 

I’m mostly the latter (price action) but the former is certainly useful for keeping a high comm rate. I think the fundamentals are also more suited to the math whizzes and ones who understand the sport more - and I’m neither of those!
